{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_rigoletto_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608786/1958060601/0489.xml":{"full_text":"\u2018A Ihi^^li 2 jC^Sfc.\nj\u00dfl&J^v\nvbbl \\^h\nBIG CLEANUP JOB\u2014Mrs. Delmar Kressin still manages a wistful smile\nas she surveys her car, battered by Wednesday\u2019s tornado at Colfax, Wis.\nHer equally battered home is in the background.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nWisconsin Storm Loss\nRuns Into Millions\nMENOMONIE, Wis., June 6 UP).\u2014 While the grim search\nfor additional dead continued, the first slow steps toward\nrecovery have been taken in this tornado-ravaged section of\nWisconsin.\nState. Federal and private agencies offered assistance\nfrom headquarters set up in the four-county area in the north-\nwest portion of the State. At\nleast 30 persons died when\nthree twisters ripped a 90-mile\nswath through the sector\nWednesday night. Six persons\nwere reported missing.\nMore than 350 persons were\nInjured, 119 of them requiring\nhospital attention. At least\n20 of the injured remained in\ngrave condition today.\nDamage in Millions\nDamage will be counted in\nthe millions, according to Gov.\nVernon Thomson, who inspected\nthe area by plane and car yes\nterday. The Red Cross said that\n615 families were affected. More\nthan 100 homes were destroyed,\nanother 165 damaged exten\nsively. and another 340 less\ni seriously. An estimated 1,000\nhead of cattle were killed.\nGov. Thomson said the initial\nrecovery moves were being\nspearheaded by local authorities\nwho have the situation well in\nhand.\nAt the same time the Gover\nnor appealed to President Ei-\nECONOMIC\nContinued From First Page\n1 was much greater than the j\ndrop in unemployment mainly\nbecause most of those added to\nagricultural employment were 1\nhousewives and students who\nhad been outside the labor\nforce in April.\nThe sizable reduction in un\nemployment was partly offset\nby an increased number of\nstudents who entered the labor\nmarket to look for summer or\npostgraduation jobs.\nTax Cut Barked\nMeanwhile, a number of lead\ning businessmen have given\nqualified backing to tax cut\nting as an anti-recession meas\nure.\nThe business leaders, re\nsponding to a questionnaire\nfrom the Senate Finance Com\nmittee, were by no means en-\nLOST\nCAT. (tar and white vicinityGlebe\nand Old Dominion: home, Fairfax:\nliberal reward. FE 3-3684.\nCAT. male, black and white, bronie\nback and tall: Tlclnltr of 69 Under\nwood n w.; liberal reward. RA. 6-\n7739.\nDIAMOND UNO, woman'!. Tic. 13th\nand Maas or 13th and M. also 14th\nand H or 7th at. wharf; reward.\nWO. 6-7034.\nDIAMOND CUTTIN, Wad. after\nnoon, Anderson House or taxi:\nGeorgetown: reward. HO. 2-2891.\nDOG. beagle, Mar 31st. male, scarred\nnose: vie. Queens Chapel rd. and\nBaltimore bird. UN. 4-3265.\nDOG, lost about 1 week, cocker, male,\nbull: D. C. license 30202: reward.\nEM. 3-1788.\nI DOG; Tic oien Hills. Rockville area:\nmixed English springer and cocker\nspaniel, male, white with black spot*:\nans name \"Chico.\" Reward PO\n\u25a0l-9036, after 8\n1 eyeglasses, ladr's: June 3, p.m.,\n6-6268\nHANDBAG, medium else, brown alll\ngator: no identification: lost Tic\nTilth and H n.w\u201e bus stop, Frl., a m\nOL 2-1356.\nPARAKEET, 1 green, toes missing on\nleft foot. Reward and exchange\nJA. 2-262 B.__eves.\nPARAKEET, yellow, leg band with\n\"40\": ans. to \"Mike\"; Tic. Bethesda:\nreward. WH. 2-3759.\nPARAKEET. blue. talks: \"Pretty\nBaby\": Tic of Woodmont. Bethesda;\nreward _ OL. 2-7986.\nPARAKEET, green with reiloir face,\nred band No D 57-19: vie. Silvel\nSprint; reward. JC- 9-1923.\nPARAKEET, turquoise blue: ans. t\u00ab\n\"Chuckv Bor\": vie. 36th ave-Queen,\nChapel rd.: reward. WA. 7-3048.\nREWARD for finding diamond ant\nrubv earring, vie. Macomb and 36tl\nsts. n.w. EM. 3-2608.\nSILVER BUTTERFLY PIN, lost Tic. o:\n11th and Mass. ave. and 16th ant\nN Y. ave Reward. HU. 3-3200\nWALLET, ladr's. dark green: vie. La\nlayette sq. and No. 20 streetcar; re\nward. AD. 4-9869.\nWATCH, mane. chronograph tvpe\nsteel case, brown seddle-typc band\nreward. LU. 2-6X44.\nI WRIST WATCH, lady'a. white gold\nnr. the Hot Shoppe In College Perk\nreward OL. 2-8830.\nD-4 bus or No. 50 streetcar. WO\nFOUND\nI RABBIT, white; vie. Aspen sc. Cal\nKl 9-3959.\nDOC. mixed breed, female, 3 mos\nbrown; vie. Hilltop terrace. Call K1\n9-3959 _\nDOG. mixed breed, male, white am\nblack; vie. N. Earl st. Call KL 9\n3939.\nDOG. part Welsh terrier, male. 4 mos\nvie. N. Washington st. Call KI. 9\n3959,\nI PARAKEET, light blue, female an\nbanded, vie. Alex.. RosemonL TE. t\ni\nsenhower for Federal emergency j I\nhelp in three of the damaged I\ncounties\u2014Dunn, Chippewa and i I\nSt. Croix. Damage in Eau I\nClaire County was less severe.! I\nThree Disaster Areas\nAs Gov. Thomson issued his I\nplea, the Small Business Ad- I\nministration In Washington an- I\nnounced it had designated the j I\nthree counties as disaster areas, I\nmaking homeowners and busi- 1 1\nnessmen eligible for loans at I\n3 per cent interest. The De-11\npartment of Agriculture an- j I\nnounced plans to make surplus 11\nfood available, as well as recon- I\n1 struction loans for farmers.\nIn the event the President\ndesignates the counties as an\nemergency relief area, the aid\ncould take the form of tem\nporary financial assistance to\nthose eligible.\nThe National Guard remained\non duty In the village of Col\nfax, hardest hit by the twisters.\nthusiastic about the idea of\ntax reduction.\nMost of the 14 men polled\nby the committee favored cau-:\ntion in employing Government\naction to bring about an eco\nnomic upturn. There were ex-'\npressions of concern that such\naction might spur inflation.\nNine of the business leaders\nsupported tax cutting in vary- j\ning degrees. Several said such\na move should be considered\nif the recession deepens. A few\ncalled for repeal or modification\nof transportation levies. In\ngeneral, tax reduction was pre\nferred over public works.\nWorse Post-War Slump\nIn their replies, prepared\nduring the past four months,\nseveral of the business execu\ntives said they thought this\nrecession is worse than pre\nvious postwar slumps in 1948-\n1949 and 1953-1954.\nA separate study prepared by\nthe staff of the Senate-House\nEconomic Committee said that\nsince its last analysis in Feb\ni ruary \u201ceconomic activity has\ncontinued to decline and there\nare as yet few signs of an early\nupturn.\u201d\nIt said that even on the basis\nof optimistic assumptions, un\nemployment in the first three\nr. months of 1959 might total\nbetween 5 million and 5.5 mil\n;j lion, with a less rapid recovery\nd possibly bringing jobless to as\nmany as 7 million persons.\ni\u2019.\n\nir\nLife of Cork Trees\nLISBON.\u2014Cork trees live 300\nj. to 400 years and may be strip\nc ped every 10 years or so. The\nbest commercial varieties ol\nn cork are obtained when the\ntrees are 40 to 50 years old.\nh\nPATIO^\nBLOCKS\n12\u201cxl6\"\u2014in Colors\n45\u00ab\nOutdoor Fireplaces.\nGarden Tools,\nBrick. Sand. Cement.\nBuilding Supplies\nME. 8-4840\nJA. 7-0411\n1 Open Saturday\nTill 12:30\n!j\nRosslyn Circle, Vo.\ni I End of Key Bridge\nTwelve of the victims died in\nthis community of 1,000 resi\ndents. Nearly half the town\nwas flattened.\nBIG J?A\nI CONTRACT\n1 Budget Terms JBL a\n2 Radio Equipped Trucks\ntor Emergencies\n3 Automatic Refill Service\nwith Metered Delivery j; f j\n4 Thrifty Heating Contracts\n5 Service Office Never Closes\nI (RIFFITH- k I\nI (ONSUMERS Sjh|\n1 1413 New York Ave. N.W. L-^ ''E\nI\n\nYOU CAN\nFIND A BETTER\nBOURBON 11\nBUY IT\u201d n 1\n...uui II\n1 AAf^*^***^\n(Us\nWe, and we alone, make every drop of Ancient Age. superb bourbon is always the same...drink after\nWhat\u2019s more. Ancient Age is made in one place only, drink, bottle after bottle. That\u2019s why Ancient Age\nat the distillery in Frankfort, Kentucky, in the is the largest selling six year old Kentucky Straight\nheart of the great bourbon country. We use nothing Bourbon in America today! Kentucky Straight Bourbon\nbut original and genuine Ancient Age bourbon. Whiskey 6 Years Old \u202286 Proof \u00a9Ancient Age Distilling\nThat\u2019s why, the distinctive taste and bouquet of this Company, Frankfort, Kentucky.\nj 1 j|iaeiy*|\u00a7\u20ac boirkoi\nJ i S 9\nMcElroy Defends Plan\nFor T roop Cutback\nBy L. EDGAR PRINA\nStar St\u00bb\u00ab Writer\nDefense Secretary McElroy\ntold Senators today that the\nworld situation does not re\nquire that we keep the Army\nat 900,000 men and the Ma\nrine Corps at 200.000.\nReferring to the action by\nthe House yesterday In voting\nadditional funds to bar cuts of i\n30,000 In the Army and 25,000\nIn the Marines by June 30,\n1959, the Secretary said in\ntestimony before the Senate\nAppropriations Subcommittee:\n\u201cAs we see the situation to\nday, there is no requirement for\nnumbers of military personnel\nin excess of those requested in\nthe President\u2019s budget for 1959.\n\u201cAs a matter of fact, as mod\nem weapons enable a man to\nincrease his military effective\nness\u2014and if the recently en\nacted amendments to the Ca\nreer Compensation Act have\nthe desired effect of retaining\ngreater numbers of skilled mil\nitary personnel \u2014It should be\npossible for us to contemplate\nsome further reduction in total\nnumbers in the years ahead.\u201d\nTransfer Authority\nMr. McElroy urged the Sena\ntors to vote the Defense De\npartment authority to transfer\nup to SSOO million in appro\npriations from one service to\nanother under the 1959 budget.\nThis would be five times the\namount permitted under the\nHouse-approved measure.\nThe Secretary said that al\nthough the President originally\nhad requested authority to\ntransfer $2 billion, subsequent\nsupplemental requests totaling\nicqucow uwumuift\n$1.6 billion had diminished the\namount of transfer authority\nneeded. He added that SSOO\ni million \u201cshould enable us to\n\nmove promptly to capitalise\nupon any unexpected develop\nments or technological break\nthroughs.\nIn voting a $38.4 billion de\nfense budget yesterday, the\nHouse cut administration re\nquests totaling $907 million and\nincreased appropriations for\nother items by sl.l billion.\nNo Funds Mandate\nMr. McElroy said the De\nsense Department would ac\n-1 cept some of the cuts bul\nurged restoration of others\nHe asked, for example, that\n1 $358 million for aircraft span\nI parts, $lO4 million for Navi\nshipbuilding and $lO7 mllliox\nfor operation malntenanc<\nfunds be restored by Senate\nj action.\nThe Secretary did not pro\n\u2014HERZOG'S DOWNTOWN CAPITOL HILL\noeep S..JI\nH short shorts\ngive you\nfreedom\nand coolest\nof comfort\nWith these amazing Geeps, you get greater freedom of move\nment because the leg opening adjusts os you move. No sag\nging either as the fabric is flat across the seat. Actually up\nto 50% cooler than other knit briefs, Geeps olso provide\nfirm, masculine support. Perfect for sports, leisure ond every\nday. Exclusively ot Herzog's in red, blue, canary, green, block\nor white. Sizes 28 to 44.\nr HERZOG'S\u2014IOth F St*. N.W., Washington, D. C.\nl Please send me the following Geeps at $1 a pair:\nI \u201csize |88130|32134|36 138140 I <2 I jjjj\nI COLO* I I I I I I I I I\nQUANTITY I I I I I I I I I I\nj NAME\nADDRESS\nAdd 25c for Moiling. Add 2% Sales Tax if D. C. Resident\nHERZOG'S\nDOWNTOWN: 10th and F Streets N.W.\nCAPITOL HILL: 205 Penna. Ave. S.E.\ntest too vigorously the in\ncreases voted by the House but\nhe said that \u201cwe would not\nregard\" the action in voting\nadditional funds \u201cas a man\ndate to pursue the various pro\ngrams on a crash basis without\nt regard to feasibility or deslra\nblltty.\u201d\nHe said he assumed that\nCongress would want to make\n\u201cfrequent technical reapprai\ne sals\u201d of its various programs\nand use the extra money when\nd It Is clearly warranted.\nir Senator Chavez, Democrat of\nNew Mexico, chairman of the\nsubcommittee said earlier he\nexpects the Senate to back the\nHouse 